comment: Prof. Yarmolinskaya is a wonderful lecturer and typically structures her classes the same (well-planned lectures along with weekly discussion posts, 2 exams, and a larger project). At times, it can be hard to apply what you are learning but such is the nature of linguistics classes of these types. Genuinely enjoyed her class and very friendly!

OS is an important class and thus couldn't skip despite the extremely poor teaching. Prof just reads off the slides - accents are fine (you learn to understand your teach) but he rambles on really fast and swallows lots of words - thnks to which only Chinese kids remain in the class. There is no connect with HW and labs are pretty bad as well.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Group projects--Clear grading criteria

comment: Professor Ender is very sweet; she cares a lot about her students and is always willing to help. I would recommend Heart Matters to students who are genuinely interested in the course's topics (the lectures can be quite lengthy, good bit of reading). She is a little disorganized but won't hesitate to further explain instructions if needed.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Caring

comment: Professor Ender is a wonderful teacher. She is passionate about the subject she teaches and she is passionate about helping her students do the best they possibly can.

Intro to computing is probably one of the easiest classes you will ever take. Prof is really nice, lenient with extra credit and missed assignments etc. I wouldn't take the class if you want to learn in-depth programming stuff though

Had her for History of Medicine. Professor Hanson is enthusiastic about the material; her lectures are quite interesting. She's kind and willing to help outside of class. TAs do a lot of the grading; they are kind as well and give great feedback. There are many extra credit opportunities; overall not difficult, pay attention and you'll do well.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Professor Chirinos is a wonderful teacher. She explains things clearly and is straightforward, which is helpful in a language class. She is very kind and willing to help/clarify. She is a fair grader and her classes are very engaging. She cares about her students and genuinely wants them to do well. Focus and work hard and you'll succeed.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: I absolutely loved taking Nate Brown's Craft of Fiction class. He is warm, caring, and considerate and really wants us all to do our best in becoming writers. I very much hope to take him again while at college.

He's a well respected professor, but he's got a bluntness about him that verges on rudeness sometimes. Couldn't go through the course because of certain interactions that I had with him, and the feedback from students that I got. He's renowned in his field and I've heard stellar things about his work but I'd recommend auditing thoroughly.
Extraordinary professor and mentor. If you really want to learn statistics at an advanced level, he's your man.
Best prof at jhu, hands down

Amazing professor. Very passionate, wise, and social. Homework is very gratifying. Homework is structured in such a way that you must read his slides or watch his lectures. Google will not help much for this class. Very lenient grader. Midterms during Covid were open note with 12 hours to complete.

Professor Tran is, by far, the best professor I have had at JHU so far. I took his class my freshman year and the stuff he teaches you is still relevant far into the future. His first unit is pretty hard stuff, but once you get past that everything else is a cakewalk. Tran is also super helpful if you go to office hours, so make sure to attend!

He's a really helpful guy, and cares about your success, which is somewhat rare in this department. Unfortunately, I feel like he breezed over a lot of fundamental concepts and his slides were tough to learn from, with very little explanation. Good guy, mediocre class for those who know nothing about ECE already.

GREAT GUY, genuinely cares about his students.  Go to his office hours. Lectures are very boring but he sometimes gives out homework solutions and info about the next lab so go anyway.  If you keep up with the hw then everything is fairly easy. Do his practice exams, midterms are fair.
Great teacher!! LOVED this class!
Very good professor. Provides lots of helps and really cares whether or not you learn. Go to Office Hours, they're amazingly helpful. Textbook is useless, don't buy it.
Genuinely cares for his students, tests are not very difficult and grading is fair, maybe even lenient. Highly recommended.

EXTREMELY HELPFUL outside the classroom. You practically just have to show up for his office hours and you will be guaranteed a decent grade. Lectures do get boring but it beats so many other classes I've had. The guy is really nice and has a sincere interest in making sure you understand the material. GREAT PROFESSOR!!!Best one I've had at Hopkins

Nice guy, but his lectures are rather boring. His powerpoints cover everything he says in lecture, to the point where you don't need to attend. Very helpful outside of class. Expect the unexpected on tests!
No Comments
VERY well organized and prepared for lectures.  Also very helpful.  Lectures can get a bit dry at times, but still better than the average ECE lecture.
Cool guy. He looks **** though. His class is easy and fair. Very approachable
Great lectures!
Hated it, the tests were an L waiting to happen. Don't recommend
An A is super easy to get in this course by just doing the backtests he posts online before the midterms and the exam

Barbera's full of himself... He always talks about himself. He's a pretty bad teacher though, to be honest. His lectures/exams/HW don't follow the book, though it's still a good resource. Exams are WAY harder than HW. Lectures are USELESS. Don't take unless required. I hear it's better if you have prior experience. TA was trash. Good curve though
ratingTags: Tough Grader--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Tests are tough

comment: Difficult exams, don't need to go to lecture

I took this class in fall 2016 and the lectures were hilarious. You don't need to go to class to do well but it's really entertaining. The class is not exactly easy but if you do the work you will be fine. Also I highly recommend going to his office hours. Barely anyone goes and it's a 300 person class!

Great professor. He makes the lectures very entertaining and relevant to current events. You can do well in the class by either focusing on the lecture material and reviewing the slides or just reading the textbook. The most important thing is that you do some practice problems. If you can't understand basic algebra, you will not understand econ.

His intro to macro class is pretty simple. He goes over a lot of non-essential material in lectures and gets on a lot of tangents, but he is pretty funny and the lectures are mostly pretty interesting. If you skim the textbook before lectures and go to class, you should be fine. The tests aren't very difficult and they have a giant curve.

His Into to Macro class is pretty straight forward. He goes over way more in lecture than is actually on the tests, but he is a funny/nice guy who adds lots of insights and keeps lectures engaging (most of the time). One of my favorite professors.
Goes off on many tangents about Lacrosse. Best way to succeed is to read the textbook.

Elements of Macroeconomics is a good introduction class and Barbera does a decent job teaching the material. It's necessary to read carefully because Barbera sometimes rambles about random stuff instead of teach the important material, but there isn't excessive reading so it's not hard to keep up with the work. Tests are hard, but curved.
Always willing to answer questions during class and office hours

She is super sweet and is genuinely willing to spend time talking to you. Explains concepts relatively clearly and always gives suggestions on how to improve. I ended up doing somewhat poorly on one of the midterms and went to go talk to her about it, and she was extremely supportive and encouraging.
She is a true bae, anyone who doesnt love this pearl of a woman has issues and needs to take gen bio I with her because she is the bestest sweetheart one could ever meet.
Gen Bio Lab is pretty clear cut. Just follow the guidelines and an A is extremely feasible. Lab was very fun and short. Pearlman is very kind and fun to talk to.
She's a really good professor and you can tell she actually cares. She teaches thing in a really easy way to understand. Don't listen to all the haters. One of the few nice people at this school.
Yay! Thanks, Prof. You rock!!!
Jolly woman.  She's really nice if you go and talk to her.  Class is not very good though.  Bad organization but easy A.

PowerPoints are a mess, but Dr. Pearlman places emphasis on what could be on the exam. Does a lot of CPS questions, so go to class. Almost 50% of her exam questions are from previous years, so STUDY PAST EXAM QUESTIONS. Posts helpful Bio Workshop questions, which are on the exam, exactly in the same format. Do past exam questions!

She is very unprofessional and it takes her forever to reply to email or post grades. It's easy to do well in the course (esp. considering that half the test questions are repeats from previous exams), but she doesn't take her work seriously. Summary: She is an embarrassment to an otherwise excellent JHU Biology Department.

This class is incredibly unorganized. There are three different professors with different teaching styles. Pearlman's lecture slides have obnoxious color schemes and are hard to keep track of. They take very simple material and make it confusing with poor organization. Not to mention, she skips material when she is in a rush to finish a lecture.

Why are people complaining about Dr. Pearlman? She is an friendly and devoted teacher who wants her students to understand the material and do well. One thing you should though, if you have any pressing questions email McCarty or Shingles. Pearlman doesn't give quick replies.

Dr. Pearlman certainly teaches like a high school teacher, but it truly helps us understand the information.  Pay attention in lecture, and you'll do fine.  She explicitly states what you will and will NOT need to memorize/understand for the test.  She is also very understanding when it comes to being sick/having family emergencies.
Super friendly.  One of the nicest and most lenient profs ever!

Dr. Pearlman may teach us like high school students, but it's not because she disrespects us. She actually cares whether or not we understand and learn, unlike most other professors here who couldn't give a damn about us.

I agree with everyone.  She would be a great high school or middle school teacher, but with Hopkins students in her class, it's just insulting.  Like someone already said, what professor asks questions to a 300 person class.  She is also great at coming up with busy work projects that waste students time and dont teach them anything helpful.

Talks down to us sometimes, but overall she is a good lecturer. She's extremely helpful and concerned about her students. She'll say every other slide, "this could be on the exam," so just know everything for the exams and you'll be golden. The course is easy but there is a lot of material so break your studying into small pieces and do old exams.

I love Dr. Pearlman.  She's really friendly and shows a true interest in her students and an excitement for her subject.  She is extremely helpful and patient  and shows a genuine concern for her students.  I loved her class!
shes mean
She teaches us like high school students.  I would respect her if she would respect me.

She is a very nice teacher.  However, she teaches to much like a high school teacher.  She aks questions in a 300 person lecture.  A good proffesor could teach as much in 20 minutes as she does in an hour.  I have begun to hold the class in contempt.  Why should I be taught like a 14 year old at one of the best universities in the world?
No Comments
She's nice.  I think she explains things well and is always willing to help.
very nice professor, always smiling. she is interested in helping students, which may be why there is a large line outside her office when she has office hours.
Great professor. Really emphasizes thinking outside the box and being creative. Challenges you to think critically and differently. A little bit crazy but truly one of a kind.
One of the best professors I had.
Thakor acts like he hates the class, but in the end, he is a nice guy.
very very bad person
He is the best and he gives really informative and funny lectures that make information stick. Already want to take another class with him!
He is a real gem. Best professor ever!!!!

Chaz makes intro psych fun with his engaging lectures. Hes super approachable and puts a lot of effort into his class. Just be aware that, unlike the rest of the class, his tests are not all fun and games.
SO many profs here barely care about teaching. Firestone is the exception. He makes you love psychology as much as he does!! Just actually go to class and the exams aren't that hard
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: He skips so many major topics which you would expect to have in Psych101 but spends hours on insignificant and trivial details. He assigns a textbook which has nothing to do with the lectures or the exams (the exams require you to memorize every single sentence he's ever said). His showmanship might be fun, but it impairs his teaching abilities.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment: Prof. Firestone is an amazing professor. He puts a lot of time and effort into making sure that learning in his class is both captivating and fun. His course webpage is nicely managed, and he adds a nice touch before every lecture with music. I am truly saddened that my intro psych journey has ended. It was a blast! I really recommend his class.

Great prof, attendance is required to get a good grade. Slides posted don't have too much material. Exams are very different than other Hopkins exams, very memorization heavy, however, they aren't too difficult. Large percentage of the class ends with an A. Just an extremely fun class to take when you want to fill out your schedule.
Engaging professor. You'll do well if you attend class and listen.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Hi Chaz! Thanks for making me love psychology so much! Im really grateful I took your class first semester :)

Dr. Firestone is one of the best professors at Hopkins. If you have a chance to take one of his classes, do it - you won't regret it. He cares about his students and does everything he can to make everything fun and the grading fair.
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: The tests were at times really unclear and took the fun out of the class. His lectures are some of the best I have seen though, but his slides are not really helpful for reviewing material outside of class because there is not much text. Be cautious.
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: Fun. Funny. Interesting. Easy.
Best professor I have ever had.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment: The only professor who made me feel legitimately sad when a class ended. Suffice to say the second another class shows up being taught by Chaz, I will be the first to register (or first on the waitlist when SIS crashes again).
ratingTags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Chaz was easily the best lecturer/teacher I've ever had and probably will have. It didn't feel like I was sitting in a 450 person class. He puts so much work into the material and cares that his students learn and appreciate it. He even takes the time to answer questions! I looked forward to going to class every day, ily Chaz.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment: Great professor
Amazing professor. Easily the best professor I've had at Hopkins. He puts in so much effort and is extremely passionate. Highly suggest taking his class.
Incredible teacher.
Amazing class that always has engaging lectures taught by a phenomenal guy.
Cannot say enough good things about this man. Ask him to show you grappling.

Professor Firestone has made a seemingly dull intro-level class with nearly 400 students very fun and exciting with each lecture. He. and all the TA's put in so much effort. The tests are reasonable and test what you learn. I wish I could take another class taught by Chaz.
Best professor ever. Engaging and funny lectures that are relevant. Also he's super cute. You deserve the chili Chaz
Hilarious very extra (awesome) man. Plays music during class and has a great sense of humor. Super engaging. Id take this class a thousand times.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment: Best professor at Hopkins. Exams are reasonable with no tricks; if you know the content youll do well. The lectures are amazing - Chaz puts in a ridiculous amount of effort and it shows. Also always approachable outside of class and takes a genuine interest in his students success, and an entertaining and quirky guy overall.
He's a beast.
Great lecturer who engages the students, even though it's a class of 400 people.

His lectures were designed to be death by PowerPoint, regurgitation of the textbook. If you couldn't understand the textbook, good luck getting clarification on the subject from watching his lectures. His class was all tests, no homework. Other than a practice midterm & final, he didn't provide supplementary practice materials to his students.

Just your average college course, nothing special. Homework and test questions were straight from the book. Read the book and you'll be fine. The course didn't really inspired students to be creative with the material and provided no opportunity for students to apply some of the statistical tools they learned in a meaningful way.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: If you like nitpicking, she's the one.

This course was no joke to say the least. Math involved was sometimes very challenging. Prof. Briand was always there and readily available to help. She posted replies to discussion boards same day, and always responded to emails within hours! She was always ready to help, and always understanding. Really glad I took this class with her!

The professor is very nice and gives good feedback on papers. There are only 2 papers in the entire semester in which your grade is based on. If you aren't some star writer, this course will be hard. She is good at teaching, but her grading criteria is not clear either. I wouldn't take her again for the fact that I like my GPA.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment: Dr. Goralski is a good professor. In the class there are not any lectures and you have to read the textbook... so its a self taught class if you will. He does respond fast to emails and answers questions quickly though so thats a pro. The assignments of the class are fairly easy as well. Overall, his class is easy as long as you read the text.

If you already have a strong command of mol bio, this is the professor to take. This class won't make you waste time if you've already taken plenty of mol bio and don't need to be taught it again. Exam questions were challenging but fair. No lectures, so you can skim readings and see if you need to refresh any concepts in more detail.

Dr. Spall is one of the most strict professor from AMS department, but, you will learn a lot from his class. He put lots of time prepare his class, lecture notes, and literatures. You will struggle in his class, overwhelmed with homeworks and quizz and exams, but you will learn a ton after the class.

Clearly knows his subject material. Grading can be a little tough (he tends to be nitpicky about careful writing and notation). Exams are generally fair but somewhat time-consuming, so need to work efficiently or risk not finishing. Hard grader who doesn't tend to give much partial credit.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Professor Spall was one of the best professors I had at Hopkins. However, his courses are very tough. Do not expect any of his courses to be walk in the park. In fact, expect them to be far more difficult than the average course. That being said, his courses are very rewarding. I wish I had taken every one of his courses while at Hopkins.

He was the worst professor I've had at Hopkins. Failed to update material for an online course. The grades section had different due dates than the individual modules, and the syllabus. He barely responded to emails, and didn't respond to most Discussion board Q&A. ZERO feedback so you could improve between assignments. AVOID AT ALL COST!! HORRIBLE
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Fair grader
subjective grader, not flexible
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: No clear grading criteria, very subjective
Didn't provide evaluation rubric
Clear and supportive.
A lot of work but very fair.  The class involves a lot of cases which are both interesting and fun.
Clear
Great guy! Very fair with grading. Knows the subject very well!
Be prepared to do all the work yourself
His exams include stuff not covered in class. Does not return assignments on time. Duplicitous and inflexible

Dr. Wellman is the best! I learned A LOT from her epigenetics course. I felt challenged but never overwhelmed. Exams are takehome essays and really reinforced the material/were very effective exercises ensuring we remembered everything we learned and could tie it all together independently. She takes pride in teaching and is very skilled at it.

Professor Wellman was by far the best and most caring professor I've had at JHU AAP! She takes the time to record video lectures and reads through all assignments/emails. The midterms are take home and very detailed, helping reinforce the material. She also ties in her research and current events to class topics. Would highly recommend!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment: Dr Greene's teaching style is very 'keep it as simple as possible, but no simpler'. Beginner level CS concepts can be tough to teach, but even intermediate programmers will likely learn a thing or two still. Take home finals that were challenging but doable. Great intro class for fundamental skills with an emphasis upon those important for bioinfo

For an ISET course, it's rather lackluster. No 3D model building or VR for example. The final project is the only thing worth boasting about and that proved to be less valuable. As for Sack himself, I think Krieger should consider placing people where they're needed. I think he does VR/AR work, but he didn't fulfill the class description.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: I was really hesitant abou this professor because of these reviews, but it was a decent class. PROS: a lot of mini and fun assignments due every week that actually allows you to apply the material (he's really generous on grading) CONS: The Quizzes ARE WAY TOO SPECIFIC/ YOU HAVE TO REALLY READ THE TEXTBOOK. The Final wasn't so bad. Give him a try!

Professor Mahr is very disorganized. He misses posting assignments on time, yet does not give you extra time to complete them. He tells you to both use and not use outside sources for reference, expecting you to learn from wikipedia or your own searches. Low quality teaching, do not recommend.

The professor is scattered and the weekly assignments are different activities every week. I spend more time reading the instructions than doing the assignments. No exams but there are weekly quizzes. The quizzes are based on the textbook and rarely on lectures. The class was wasn't difficult but the tedious. There's always things to do each week.

Dr. Mahr is scattered. His instructions for assignments warns against spelling and grammatical errors. Yet his communications were riddled with them. It made figuring out what topics are important for tests and quizzes a challenge. Don't expect feedback. That said, he grades fairly and transparently. He's personable in his lectures and emails.
Calc3- Quite an asynchronous class. Workload is doable and not hard.

About 8 hours of math homework a week and weekly quiz. I thought I was good at math until I took cal 3. To be fair, he didn't have the chance to lecture a lot since the lecture videos were pre-recorded. Still, the hardest class I've ever had. Questions are so hard they'll screw you over even if you know cal 1,2, and 3 like the back of your hand.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment: I took her class years ago and doubt much has changed. She made me dread class and sucked so much joy out of learning for me. I don't remember many specifics apart from how condescending she could be. I got the impression she didn't like what she was doing. Her classes didn't emphasize reading, writing, speaking, or listening. Low value.
Unclear explanations. Dismissive. Takes all fun out of learning.

Awful - Unhelpful and dismissive. Her attitude is "sink or swim" and she won't offer suggestions on how to avoid sinking. She doesn't care about students at all. Comes across as nice on the outside. Her classes have a 50% drop out rate. She's tenured so less work for her.

Professor Johnson is very lively and outgoing, she brings a lot of light into the classroom when she lectures. She comes across a little naive during lecture, but she will make every effort she can to help her students understand what is going on in the class. She's very passionate about Japanese language, and makes learning exciting and fun.

Great professor, very accessible during office hours and by email. Lecture-style is the only rough part. He goes very fast and throws in a lot of proofs that never show back up on any assessment. Grading is fair (but no curve). Tests are hard, not much partial credit on Sapling, but generally fair.
Lectures go off topic and have too much info stuffed in, difficult to study for exams, exams are unreasonably hard
he made me hate chemistry
He can be annoying and he moves really quickly during lectures, but he is kind of funny during lectures sometimes.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment: Dr. McCloskey is a true gem. His class structure provided a timeline to easily get all of the asynchronous work done and actually learn the material. He's a funny guy and his online lectures are easy to follow and very interesting. Taking his class confirmed that I want to study neuroscience because it's a really great intro to the field.

I had McCloskey for Visual Perception, which was the hardest class I've taken besides CogNeuro. His tests were difficult and not straightforward at all-even if you knew the material you could easily get confused by his questions and do poorly. Our grade was mostly based on these exams. He would also make inappropriate political jokes in class
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES

comment: Best professor ever

Dr. McCloskey is by far the best professor I ever had. The best thing about him is that he really has an incredible insight on the class materials he thought, and most of the time he was hesitant on agreeing with the case studies discussed in class. And that's a good thing cuz that's how science should be..too bad he taught only 2 classes here

Dr. McCloskey is an excellent teacher because he engages his students and encourages them to learn, instead of making them. He was my favorite teacher thus far because he made class interesting with case studies, made it funny with his humorous jokes, and made coming to class worthwhile. Because I wanted to learn, it became and honor to be in his c
very interesting class. I enjoyed it. There are lots of quizzes but it takes like 2minutes and really really really easy. However, the midterm and final is quite difficult and ambiguous.

Due to online class behavior, the lectures are not as excited as they could be as if we were learning in a real classroom. However, the materials are quite comprehensive and easy to digest if you really dig in some time into them.
Extremely boring lectures

Tifft is so nice! I took biochemistry online with her and she made it so much more bearable. She simplifies concepts, regularly checks Piazza, and is super helpful in office hours. I will be taking another class with her next semester. I just wish the other biochem profs followed her example because she is truly amazing. Not a hard class either!
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: The classes are very well structured. I'm just not good at biochemistry...
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Tough grader

comment: Dr. Ziad is a gem of a human being. She is kind, caring, and open to discussion of all worldly issues. She opened up to students in her class, showing her empathy and lack of hesitation to become familiar with the students. An amazing person, professor, and friend. Highly recommend her class for anyone interested in Islam. Lots of reading!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Awful. Hardest grader for chem lab I have ever had. Doesn't explain anything in the prelab lecture and expects you to know things you haven't even learned yet.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: have this lady for lab and lemme just say, DO NOT TAKE HER. She speeds through the powerpoints and we barely have time to take notes cuz she goes so fast. also she randomly calls on the same 5 people casually in the middle of lecturing. post labs are hard cuz she doesn't explain things. DO NOT TAKE HER UNLESS YOU WANT TO SUFFER. DO NOT TAKE!!!!

I'm currently taking organic chem 332 lab with her and she is awful. She grades unbelievably hard and takes off points for the littlest thing. Her prelab lectures are so long, repetitive, boring and a waste of time. She expects you to know everything like we are organic chemists. She gives out more work than my lecture teacher. DO NOT TAKE.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: She is one of the worst professors I have had. She has an annoying voice and she is very critical and condescending when I visit her for office hours. Also, her exams are hard and expects people to know Organic Chemistry.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--TEST HEAVY

comment: Accessible teacher, goes through the course material a bit quicker than you might like (sometimes her explanations aren't the best) but always makes herself available to help outside of class. her notes were a bit confusing but she was generous with the course's grading also. go to class & her office sometimes and you'll probably get a B+ minimum.

An amazing professor. Always accessible for office hours, will answer e-mails quickly (even over weekends or late at night), and really works hard to make sure you understand everything. Also offers extra credit on most tests/assignments and grades very well.

She curves the average to a B+ which was very generous and she also wants you to do well. She'll answer an email about a lab pretty much until 2 AM the night before it's due. However, a lot of the time she expects you to know far more than is required for the course (ex. knowing organic chem for an entry level course)
She's awesome!

Great professor. Takes office hours seriously, answers e-mails promptly and is willing to go the extra mile to help you understand something. Her online lectures are also really helpful if you do not want to attend section.

I dont know why everyone is talking about how great she is. Greco takes orgo lab too seriously. The exam averages were Fs, Ds, and Cs. She will make you work hard for a measily 3 credits. The grading was also too harsh. The only good thing I could say about her is that she gives extra credit and curves pretty well.

Dr. Greco is a great professor. She cares so much about chemistry, and she does a good job actually explaining the chemistry behind the labs we do. It's really important to come prepared to lab, otherwise it will be really stressful when you're in there trying to make a reaction happen. Go to office hours if you don't understand something!
Very good. Cares about the subject. Make sure to memorize the past exams that she posts. Very approachable during office hours
Excellent Material - high clarity in teaching. She's also really generous with grading.

Very generous with grading. Tests are easy if you read the lab handouts. Somewhat harsh on lab reports, but gives good feedback. Come to lab having read the lab. Very kind and helpful. Overall a great professor. Easy to do well.

took it in fall. approachable. clear lecturer. she tells you what you need to do. do it and you should be fine (median B+). result sheets are straight forward, quizzes are detail oriented, picky w/ lab reports, but again she tells you what she wants you to know. also, she's one of those teachers that considers improvement when giving final grades.

She was really good! I heard terrible things going into orgo lab, but actually enjoyed it.  There was a relaxed atmosphere that promoted actually teaching and learning the material (something that doens't always happen at hopkins).  A teacher I'd remember.  She is very clear in what she wants you to do - do it, and you'll get a B or above.
No Comments

The instructor is okay. I didn't see the relevance for Poli Sci, not even along political theory lines. More appropriate for Writing Sems/Philosophy. Very small class, think 4. Overall a tough grader esp for the niche course content. you can still do well but not worth the laborious exercises imo and I might've dropped if S/U wasn't a thing

A really unusual class but absolutely worth it. A lot of class is dedicated to imagining real life situations in which you'd say one thing rather than another, and this was a lot of fun. comment: There are few professors, if any, more passionate about what they teach than Brooks. Taking his courses made me decide to become a history major, that's how powerful his teaching is. It's hard to rate how hard Brooks is, because he gave final grades based on "what he thought we deserved," not our averages. It was a lot of work & he threatened to give us Cs/Ds, but most of us got As (I think lowest was a B). He tells interesting stories, but tends to ramble. He looks for very specific ideas in essays, so learn what he wants.

Professor Brooks' class, Cold War, is a lot of work and you will have to read A LOT. Honestly though, that is to be expected in most classes at Hopkins, and unlike many other classes I feel this class gave me a tangible benefit. Shes a great professor! There is alot of reading you will need to do to learn the subject and practice the problems. She provides you will all the material you need and the grading criteria is straightforward.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: Extremely vague questions, badly written problems. Will take off points for correct answers if they do not match exactly what she wanted. Very hard to understand during lecture as well.
best professor ive ever had !
He was amazinng, couldnt stop staring into those gorgeous eyes of his....
He was amazing, couldnt stop staring into his eyes the entire time....
This prof has been diabolical. He does not care about the students' success. He only cares about his own dignity. Bad lectures. Horrible personality. Never take a class with him. Ever.

Dude has a massive ego. Unwilling to listen to students and literally has told students "tough luck." If you aren't in AMS don't take him. He tried to change the syllabus midway through the (COVID) Fall semester.

Awful professor. Doesn't care to give lectures, gives 3 difficult homework every week and each of them takes at least 3 hours to complete, and then he takes most of our points off for extremely minor mistakes. Every single person taking this class and his TAs are deflated with how awful he grades. Avoid.

He tries so hard to lower students' grades by force TAs to deduct points from minor unexplained (but clearly correct) steps. I recommend non-AMS major students NOT TO TAKE HIS CLASS.

Cares more about the class grade distribution than students actually learning. His "lectures" consist of doing worksheets that no one has time for. Unreasonable grading that seems to get arbitrarily harder every other week.
Don't bother going to classes. Very mean person.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--So many papers

comment: awful

Spends very little time explaining the material in class. Tends to start class with quotes that are irrelevant to the syllabus. Grades harshly and never finishes within the 50 minute limit.
Always talks more than 50 min. Lecture notes do not have connections on textbooks nor homework. He has been rigid and harsh on students. Very disapointed at this class.

Lectures were unclear and contained few examples. The professor was uninterested in teaching the core material and decided to teach what he found more interesting. Very unclear, and lectures are not full of errors. Obviously, didn't spend enough time on teaching.
He is making the stuffs confusing than they should be. Also, he should be more organized when teaching.
Very good professor, listens to students, even asks how to improve the class repeatedly.

comment: Amazing professor. Dr. Selbie responds very quickly to any emails and provides a ton of valuable feedback in case students needs any help. ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Makes you work for it! Wants perfect answers after a lot of reading and research. But if you've put in the effort, the exams can be cracked. Perfectionist. But this course makes sure that you learn a lot!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Would recommend taking this teacher for Cell Biology at Hopkins. Was good class
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--So many papers

comment: Dr Selbie was an excellent teacher who stressed critical reasoning skills and problem solving, rather than rote memorization and regurgitation. Yes there is lots of reading, projects & quizzes/tests, but if you want to learn Biology take her
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Group projects--So many papers

comment: This class is based heavily on weekly discussions and group projects. The midterm and final are take home, essay based exams. There is quite a bit of work required in this class. Memorization is required but using the textbook for quizzes and exams are crucial. This class also focuses a lot on experiments. An A is possible but needs a lot work.

Dr. Selbie is very personable 1:1. That approachability sort of stops in class though. The group projects are pointless papers and there is no accountability. The lectures are dense and boring. The book graphics are designed by amateurs. I struggled through this class because it was so uninspiring, and classically dull.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Probably the best professor I have ever had! Took Stem Cell and Advanced Cell Biology with Selbie - very good problem solving assignments, good overviews of material (rather than worthless memorization) and group assignments help you learn the material. I would recommend her for the JHU Biotechnology program!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment: He cares about the work and assigns readings that give you multiple perspective on complex issues. You'll learn a lot; he's invested in improving your writing.

Hard to reach outside of class, but apart from that she's extremely knowledgable in Anthropology. Her perspectives and assigned readings diverge from typical canonical text, making them all the more interesting. You will learn a lot. She is willing to help you if you reach out.

Clara's lectures are long and hard to follow if you're not greatly interested in anthropology. The TA really saved the class. There are no tests, just papers which are difficult for the non-anthropologically inclined, but not too cumbersome. Participation matters. Little homework, but heavy reading.

Clara is one of the best professors I had in four years at Hopkins.  I believe that some of the other comments stem from a failure to meet her admittedly high expectations.  She assigned a lot of reading, much of which was theoretical and dense.  But if you take the time to read closely, and perhaps read things twice, you'll do well.  Your choice.

Dr. Han was one of the worst professors I had during my time at Hopkins. She was extremely biased in her teachings, often refusing to consider a student's point of view. Her lectures, while often based on excellent reading material, were difficult to follow and often missed the original point of the readings. Do not recommend.

When I was younger, I dreamt of becoming an anthropologist. Accordingly, when I signed up to take this class, I was ecstatic to begin fulfilling this dream. However, this class killed my aspiration of becoming a medical anthropologist. The professor is biased, neglectful, and the worst embodiment of medical anthropology across the seven seas.

Dr. Han, while bringing interesting readings to students' attention, is terrible at teaching. Her lectures are painful to sit through due to her incomprehensive, scattered speaking. She is horrible at responding to students with feedback, and shows obvious favoritism in the classroom. She only has ONE publication and frankly, shouldn't.

Clara Han is the most useless, lower than mediocre, insecure, teacher ever. She never ever comes prepared to any graduate class that she has taught and relies on heavy sensationalism for her undergraduate classes. In my opinion she is the Anthropology Department's biggest scam & has no publications.

Had her for an intro anthro and film class, untraditionally; she dual-taught with another prof and a TA. She is very intelligent and helpful when you ask questions. She facilitates questions and never makes you feel inferior even though you know you're nowhere near her level. Good class, good teacher.
Professor Han is a great teacher- her classes are time consuming and challenging but very educational and interesting- take any classes she has to offer!
No greater feeling than trying to find external resources just to see that it says the topic is Calc III every week
She gives a lot of work but it's nothing too difficult . You can often find the solutions online just by googling them, she just finds them from textbooks and other professor's worksheets.

Dr. Smith is a nice person, but her lectures are very frustrating to try to follow. The material isn't that hard, but half the difficulty of the class has come from the sheer work of deciphering the convoluted, redundant recorded lectures. Discussion sections are very, very superficial, but the exams require much more knowledge. Avoid this class.
ratingTags: Graded by few things--Test heavy--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: His class was really hard but there was a big final grade curve. He made question banks to help us study for the final and was always available to talk. His handwriting could be a bit better, though.

WORST TEACHER EVER! disorganized lectures and unrecognizable handwriting. Midterms were completely different from lectures and hw. When I asked him for advice, he literally told me just to relax. Refused to give us rubrics for exams and told me we would all request for regrades and annoy him. Doesn't care about his students at all!

Professor Leps is one of the best professors Ive ever had. Although Accounting can be dry, she takes the time to make sure everyone understands the material by involving class participation. Shes very receptive to questions and clarifications without judgement. Very fair problem sets and exams, & very light HW load if you pay attention in class.

comment: Good prof, Financial Accounting is boring.
She's the best. I wish she could teach other Hopkins professors how to be approachable and make the subject matter interesting.
Best professor at Hopkins

SO much homework  8 hours a week for this one class. Attendance and participation in discussion (camera on) is mandatory, but most of the time he drones on and on. It is unclear what we have to know versus what he is discussing for his own fun. This class made me cry multiple times and I reconsidered my minor twice.

I loved having Aronhime. He's very eloquent, quite funny, and truly cares about the material and his students. Grading on exams and quizzes can be tough but you truly learn a lot. I'd definitely enjoy having him as my prof again.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Thought his teaching style was pretty ineffective while I was in class but looking back I actually learned a lot.

ratingTags: Get ready to read--Beware of pop quizzes--Amazing lectures

comment: I found Professor Aronhime to be a rude and aloof Professor. He gave off an arrogant attitude that made the teaching quality in class poor. I think he lacks the guts to be humble and look at himself as being there to help students rather than self-aggrandize.

Fall 2017. This was back when it was a writing intensive class, which made the amount of work a bit excessive. Lectures were super interesting, with easy reading quizzes about once a week. Aronhime definitely is one of the better professors, because he actually has real world experience in the subject matters he taught. Curve is based on section.

Aronhime is probably the most interesting professor I've had so far at Hopkins. Unlike most of the professors here, he has real world experience that he uses to enhance lectures. His lectures are always interesting (even in a boring class like Financial Accounting), because he ties in stories about his experiences as an accountant and manager.

The lectures were always the most insightful and interesting things to sit through. Very wise man. BUT: an ample amount of busywork Advise: If Aronhime changes his voice an octave lower.. probably understand the statement fundamentally with some examples for exams. Favorite professor so far at Hopkins. Put some effort in and the A will come.
awesome guy

Lectures aren't helpful in terms of testgrade, but they are enjoyable to sit through. You can learn a lot about how the business world works from him, but I'm not talking about the test material. His stories, insight, and lectures teach much more than his powerpoints and tests. In fact, I would say his tests are unnecessarily obscure.

Aronhime knows how to keep students interested and motivated. He is an incredibly fascinating man with a true depth of knowledge in business and beyond. He has much to offer the students of Johns Hopkins.
Way too much work. Far too much homework and way too hard on the grading. His intro to business class is easy though.
Professor Aronhime is great - go to class, sit in the front of the lecture and take it all in. Its a decent amount of work but its not difficult!

He is an extremely interesting and engaging professor. There is no textbook, instead he lectures from PowerPoint Slides. Midterms are multiple choice and relatively challenging, but you get a cheat sheet. I highly recommend this course to everyone!

Excellent accounting teacher. He was able to explain the principles of accounting in a clear way and show you how things work in the real world. Great at explaining, bringing context to questions and asks great questions that really make you think. Highly rate him.
Very interesting knows what he's talking about

Lecture is somewhat entertaining/useful. Material on the powerpoints make up the midterms. Section is useful for homework. Reading material can be interesting, and he gives basic pop-quizzes just to see if you read them/for attendance purposes.
Love his stories. The tests are pretty easy.
Very efficient and clear professor. His classes are truly engaging and the best on campus. Very good TA's as well!
Good class. Annoying tests though.
He is the best!
Very interesting classes - loved his stories. However, very unclear what material/how he will test you.

TAKE INTRO TO BUSINESS.  Aronhime is awesome and it is very useful (and a W).  He is clear in his teaching and in his expectations, and will help you succeed.  You have to TRY to do poorly in his courses.
Incredibly easy class but a lot of work. Very interesting readings.
one of the best professors at hopkins
Very demanding, but great lecturer!

great lectures. and does end the semester with some interesting life lessons speech. BUT, he's very arrogant. complete narcissist. and calls on the guys in class most of the time. you'll be fine if you kiss his ass...especially if you're a girl.
The best lecturer in the school.
good guy
I really hated this class. Aronhime is a nice guy, but he hands grades out in a very random manner. There are way too many teacher's pets surrounding him for my comfort.
Down to Earth

Very good lecturer
He the man.

lectures are boring. really nice guy. i thought i was failing but there is a huge curve so it all evens out
He's fantastic!

Super active on Piazza, he really wants to make sure everyone understands the content. Seems like such a sweet guy, wish I had him for more classes.

Differential Equations with Professor Brown has been one of the best experiences I've had at JHU. Diff Eq is not an easy class, but brown definitely made it one of the most enjoyable. He has an extreme understanding of the subject and I cant wait to take his dynamical systems class. Professor Brown, "we will talk again very very soon"

Dr. Brown is an excellent professor. If you have the chance to take his class, do so. I feel like I learned so much this past semester; Dr. Brown really cares about his students doing well and he has a fair grading system. Differential equations is no walk in the park, but you'll feel satisfied when you've completed the course. Highly recommended.

Brown is a pretty nice dude, but his Calc 3 class is HARD. The written homeworks were impossible unless you had a really firm grasp of the concepts taught in class--they were all proof-based. However, he makes up for it by having tests that are purely computational, which is pretty nice. Great lectures and interesting class, but definitely not easy
Dr. Brown was an insightful, passionate professor and he made Calculus 3 very enjoyable.

Dr. Brown is the most amazing professor I have ever had in this school so far. His lectures are inspirational and well structured. The creative problems sets make you work for them, and I enjoy working with people and reaching the final solutions. The textbook is good for review and preview. His tests are relatively easy.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Inspirational--Amazing lectures

comment: Nice Guy. But a ridiculous class. Unclear grading criteria, tells ppl that he will give out "subjective" grades. Exams are all computation- with TERRIBLE numbers. Just an exhausting class.
Really funny and nice guy and knows his content very well. Really good teacher!

Had him for differential equations. He helps you truly understand what differential equations are and how you can study them. His exams are very doable if you attend class consistently and study your notes. Only complaint I can think of is his terrible handwriting.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Best math teacher/class I've ever had. Really passionate about the material and does a fantastic job explaining how everything is all tied together in a way that allows you can get a good understanding the first time through.

Class could have been easily considered way too difficult for a calc 1 class. Homework and tests graded very harshly with points being deducted for not explaining every theorem used correctly or how you got the right answer. Weekly homeworks appeared short until you realize each problem had multiple parts. Hard class, but very very generous curve.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Tests are tough

comment: Dr. Brown is a great, very personable teacher. His lectures tend to go from a deductive standpoint, rather than inductive, so keep that in mind if you learn better from examples. His tests were fair, and though they are not curved, the class is. There are only 2 midterms and a final, but a LOT of homework!
Hard class, but Prof. Brown's lectures were undoubtedly helpful. Fair amount of homework, although it's only 10% of the overall grade...

He is a good guy.  Teaches in a very general sense, which I honestly did not appreciate.  I had to do a lot of outside studying because that is not how I learn.  However, his tests are extremely fair.  If you know the material, you will succeed.

Dr. Brown is a fantastic, captivating lecturer. His class did talk mostly about theory, but he listens to what the students have to say, and adjusts his teaching style to fit the class's needs as a whole.  His tests are fair, very doable, and follow the structure of the homework. He is always there to answer questions and wants students to succeed.

When I started my semester with Dr. Brown, I was initially dismayed that the class was very theoretical in nature during the lectures, but I really think this class has made me enjoy math as an actual subject rather than a tool used to manipulate other fields. Would easily take another class from him.
He is one of the best professors I have had!

The man made me love math. His lectures are passionate and interesting. He is an inspiring force in a typically insipid education system, teaching a frequently misunderstood subject. Put in the work, and ask him loads of questions. He loves teaching, and he will make you love learning.

Prof. Brown is very easy to talk to and actually wants to help students who are struggling. He knows the material thoroughly and hopes that each of his students enjoys the class and learns the material. He is a fantastic professor. The homework assignments help in preparing for the tests.

Dr. Brown is a great teacher. He focuses a lot on the theory of mathematics, so there is a lot of writing in the class. Most of the times I think it is not helpful because he barely gives examples in class. He spends most of class proving a theorem. His tests are pretty difficult. First exam class average was a 68. Learned most from textbook..
Loves to teach and is really interested in your progress during the course.  Wants the students to learn as much as they could and get full potential out of themselves.  Great professor!

Professor is extremely interesting, funny, and engaging. He has a real passion for math and this shows. His lectures are very clear, concise, and his notes are very helpful. However, the exams are pretty hard.
What a great teacher. He really helps improve Hopkins's reputation because he really loves the topic and loves teaching people. Very professional also.

He has a very theory-based teaching style, which I'm not personally a fan of. The tests are based on homework problems so if you do those & have a good TA you'll be fine. He was very attentive to students & tried to answer questions as well as he could. I personally just had a hard time w/ his teaching style & think didn'the lectures were helpful.

One of the best professors in the department. His explanations are clear and concise and he presents the information in a logical fashion that is conducive to learning. He is also genuinely concerned with your understanding of the class and fosters a passion for the subject. Top reason why I'm a math minor.
Awesome, awesome teacher!!  I absolutely loved having him.  : )

Runs a B- curve, so beware. Says he'll take into account upward trend, but doesn't. Doesn't teach well and gives out way too much work (6 problems asking you to do the exact same thing). Lazy -- won't do things you ask him to. Doesn't really understand questions people ask. Overall, sucky professor. Don't take his course.

He doesn't actually teach all that well, but the textbook is quite helpful. DO THE HW because the tests are exactly like the hw. He does, however, like to assign incredibly theoretical questions but with a good TA and a few hours in the math help room, it is possible to do well. Fair class overall, one of the best in the department.
He dismissed automatically a few complaints about a course I had without listening.
Good teacher, really concerned with how you do in the class
His vocabulary is pretty small, but he manages to explain concepts very well. I thought his exams/final were very fair

Very easy-going prof. He really understands and loves the topic that he teaches. He encourages students' questions and seems to want everyone to pass based on their understanding of the coursework rather than just a couple of test letter grades.
The only examples he uses in class are the ones given in the book.  He is unable to teach new ideas; he just explains things as if you know them.  The book is readable tho.

Brown is great. His lectures are very clear, and he explains both the background and the use of what he teaches. Don't listen to the two reviewers above. He tries really hard to get you to understand what he does. A really cool professor.

While people have said his Calc III lectures were useless, his DiffEq lectures were very helpful. He was very helpful in answering questions and was overall a great professor. Homework was reasonable and tests reflected homework and lecture material well (and weren't extremely difficult, meaning no curve)

As someone already stated, his lectures are useless and boring. However, attending the sections is what matters. I decided to choose him for Diff. Eq's since his teaching style is "predictable" in a bad way. (No need to attend lectures)
Though class, the lectures are boring, and useless, just read the book and you will do fine.

Kaplan is so sweet as a person, but his lectures are long-winded, and take an hour and a half to summarize the 15 minute Flipitphysics prelecture. He only goes over proofs but does not go over solving or applying the concept. Homework sets are unnecessarily difficult, and the grading is pretty harsh. Assigned extra homework over spring break days.
Hardest tests ever -- Second test average was around 40, and third test average was 18 -- however, curves are generally fair so you won't fail this class if you put in effort.

Dr. Kaplan is a wonderful professor for introductory physics. He explains concepts well. Expect his tests to contain similar examples to what he uses in class. His grading system is very fair; you know exactly what your grade is at any given point in the course. The final exam is incredibly difficult, be prepared.
Good lecturer who is always using his kids as examples for motion and dynamics.  Not overly hard, but a very conceptual class.

Can you imagine my intro. to stats was taught by Prof. Naiman? I really like his way of teaching - writing in laptop touch board and projector to us in class. He asks questions on the proofs and derivatives during class which makes it a special experience. I build my confidence on stats from his 430.
He is the best instructor I ever had in all of my 15 courses. He is so cool. He spent a long time on the class. I never see a chairman hold office hours the whole afternoon like him.

I feel terrible about having to give him such bad ratings because he's such a nice guy, but his lectures are EXTREMELY hard to follow, which makes the tests very hard.  I would not recommend taking Stats II with him... wait for a semester when someone else is teaching it.
What a terrible teacher. He expects you to know wayy too much for the class and gives terrible quizzes that noone does well on. He says you don't need to know programming but you really do

No Comments

Dr. D'Souza was great. Super clear, patient lectures and a remarkably well-structured class; despite the online format, orgo lab was kind of fun with her. Though it is a sizable amount of work week to week, the work keeps you on top of things and pads your grade; exams are only 33% of your grade.
Lot of assignments-but they are pretty easy if you just do everything that is required.

Dr. D'Souza is def a nice person, but she and the TAs hurry you a lot during lab and it's kinda hard to actually enjoy the experiments. Exams are complete memorization - doable but sometimes there's no partial credit for like a 20 point question. Her grading criteria for lab reports are very clear so that's a plus.
Rote memorization to succeed on exams, but is very useful for the MCAT!
Had so much fun!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Dr. D'Souza is an amazing person who cares so much about the safety and happiness of her students. Her lab is extremely well structured and makes sure students can learn practice skills and useful information.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Caring

comment: Excellent professor overall!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: She genuinely cares about her students and really wants everybody to do well. She curves the class to a 90% and often states her grading criteria in handouts and during lectures. Make sure to pay attention to the details on her powerpoint for exams.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Caring

comment: She definitely does make you work for it. However, it is a rewarding experience. Grading wise, she's pretty clear in what she expects. Lab reports are very straight forward as she gives you the specific wording to use. Exams are challenging because there are no backtests (the legend is no one has a past exam) and she focuses on details and concepts

Larissa has a degree in editing and is very specific about wording on exams to the point where she subtracts points if you do not copy her words from lecture verbatum. Partial credit does not exist in this class and memorization of useless properties is given undue attention in this course. Morale is always low after doing anything for this class.

Larissa embodies the scientific stereotype here at JHU. She expects perfection and grades assignments on wording rather than subject matter which is a common source of frustration because no one memorizes paragraphs verbatim. Her tests pull arbitrary information from the backlogs of her slideshows. Her TA's are amazing though.

Great Prof! Really knows his stuff, always brings in real-life examples to the class. There is hw every night, and tests are difficult but he makes the material engaging. Best option for financial accounting.

Don't take this class if you value your sanity. She doesn't respond to any messages and when she does arrange for an actual meeting, she fails to show up. She says she doesn't want stuff done in a cookie-cutter approach, but that just means she doesn't want to give us a rubric to go off of. There is no direction with this class with projects/tests.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment: Don't take his QM if you have the chance. Problem sets are confusing and not self-explanatory. No syllabus posted until almost the end of the semester.

Petar is great! He gave us so much extra credit and his problem sets were actually pretty interesting at times. It's a pretty difficult subject to understand, but the TA's were always very helpful and Petar also had office hours. He even offered to meet with me outside of his office hours once because I was struggling on a concept.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Petar does not take the time in his lectures to ask if the students understand the material. He constantly refers to questions as being "quite easy" which makes students feel like they shouldn't be confused and therefore should not ask questions. He also rushes through material, talks quickly, and skips over slides often.
He is a great professor.
Petar is awesome.

I love this guy! He was so caring all throughout the semester and will actually listen to you, stay over time to make sure you understand everything. Going to his office hours was the best choice ever! If you have to take physics take it with Petar
Great teacher, I always enjoyed his lectures and found him very inspirational

This was a difficult class, but only because E&M is a difficult subject. Petar went out of his way to be availible to help students, and wanted everyone to be able to understand the subject and do their best. He put a lot of time and effort into grading fairly, and really cares about teaching.

Petar is an awesome professor. He clearly loves physics and loves teaching. Petar is always available for help. Lectures can be all over the place at times, but in general, lectures are very useful. Petar isn't a particularly difficult professor. Rather, the subject matter is what is difficult. Petar's tests are fair and based off lectures.
Lectures are mainly proofs and derivations that are not useful to the material.

NOTE: Though the people below are correct in saying his class is not easy, his curve is very generous (prob to an A- or so).                                                                                   Very funny, helpful, and genuinely interested in your understanding the material.
I had Petar for classical mechanics I and he was an amazing professor. always available for help.  although the exams were hard, he was very generous.

Petar is an amazing and enthusiastic professor.  He really cares about his students' understanding, and though his exams are ridiculously difficult, he is the ALWAYS available for extra help, if you want it.

You know what? I think teaching is just a talent. It needs not only knowledge, but also patient, and passion. Joe really likes teaching and he puts lots of time on it. Anyone having problem Joe will teach you and give you the answer.
Joe is awesome!! Goes above and beyond to make himself available to help you. He really cares about his students and is so easy to approach. I'd take another class with Joe again in a heartbeat.
Great course and great dude.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Hilarious

comment: I just have to say, if you plan on taking this class god speed. I have never taken a class this rigorous in my life. Being honest, if you have a job or a family you really don't stand a chance, because the amount of work required to do semi-well is beyond what any normal human can handle. For 4 months this class ruined my life, and I'm not joking.

Lectures: Verbally clear, but usually no visual aids. Notes copied into Powerpoint. HW: 5 very long, tedious problems, no software allowed unless stated. Discussion: Another homework problem, really? Textbook: Mostly irrelevant and unhelpful. Material: Pretty interesting. Neurodivergents: Beware. She's inflexible, assumes ill intent/dishonesty.

Waste of time and money, the teacher does not explain the course well, she just read her notes. Youtube is much better explaining the course material. long exams, very very long homework. If you want to fail take this class.
Her lectures  building a small ship Her homework  building a cruiser Her exam  building an aircraft-carrier And also, no solution provided for exams & homework Really irresponsible lecturer!
Not sure why she gets such a bad reputation from students. Shes a good lecturer and makes the class interesting.

Professor Castello is a challenging professor and taught the material quite well. Her lecture is extremely dense and requires razor sharp attention the whole time to understand what was going on. Missing a couple minutes could lead to the student being completely lost. She doesn't curve which is sad, but that doesn't mean she is a bad teacher.

Textbook is useless. Professor gave very unreasonable amount of homework involving mostly untaught definitions and theorem. Not considerate at all assign mini-assignment that is due 25 minutes after problem post. Apparently, she is not considering students might have class right after her class.

Castello provides good examples of definitions and concepts. She has solid and clear proofs - great for students with no background in proofs. She is sometimes unprepared to answer students' questions, although they are not hard questions. The class is super easy. The exams are easy but time is limited.

Homework is CHAOTIC. Keeps changing it even within 48 hours of the DDL. Very very mean professor. She does not care how students learn. You won't pass her class without any self-study. Don't bother going to the lecture. That's is what "ABSOLUTE USELESS" is for.
She is the MOST mean person I have ever met at Hopkins. She can ONLY read of from her notes and is not capable of elementary algebraic calculation. Her problem set is ambiguous and redundant.

She reads off of her notes and speaks really fast. She gives homework question that relates to next lecture, thats all fine but why grade so harshly. Tuition is $$$, why so mean? YouTube videos (not by her) have been really helpful. She says shes passionate about teaching but she probably need to reassess her abilities.
Not familiar with the course material. Unable to describe problem clearly. Most students are confused by problem set instructions.
Cannot describe problems properly in the problem sets; had to make multiple clarifications for students to understand the problem. Unfamiliar with course material.

Exams were very difficult and not curved. The class at the end of the semester was not curved, unless you were failing. Very difficult class, and the professor made no attempt to help students when it came to their grades.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: FINAL GRADES ARE NOT CURVED!! Midterms are not easy and some are impossible to finish with the time given. Lectures are useless because it is straight out of the textbook. But you still need to go to lectures to get those random unfair  bonus points she gives. Homework are long and useless as a study material for midterms and finals.

very nice teacher. lectures are clear and thorough though they can be boring at times. textbook is pretty bad but if you go to lectures you'll be fine. tests are somewhat difficult but not impossible. homework is important; no quizzes. pay attention and the class is fun.
reasonable amount of homework.  tests are not hard because you get to make a cheat sheet.
Easy easy class (math models) but SO MUCH busywork for homework that it makes u want to die.  Not so nice if she doesn't like you.
One of the nicest teachers I've ever met, she really cares about the students learning and doing well. She doesn't trick anyone in her exams, so most people get the grade that they deserve.
Good deal.  Very reasonable.

Avoid this teacher at all cost. His grading policy wasn't clear at all and he graded ppl arbitrarily on presentations. He constantly interrupted ppl when they presented and didn't answer questions in emails. He was sexist when grading presentations, as multiple ppl pointed out. Pretty much ppl's grades are dependent on 20-mins of presentations.

His class is not easy but he has a great grading system where he will drop an exam grade and offer final redemption. Going to lectures is beneficial but he doesn't care if you don't go. Do well on homework. Do as many homework problems as possible. He will curve the class fairly to a B, he isn't a jerk. But he gets frustrated if you ask questions.
Never met a professor who cared this much about whether or not we learned the material.
uh, this class was damn impossible. What's math
nitu is so elite

Excellent teacher.  He is really smart, and really clear in his lectures.  Most of what he teaches makes sense...  However, the class is nightmarishly hard.  He also assigns a lot of homework during the week.
Fantastic professor, is interested in knowing that the students understand the material, funny, and incredibly smart.
good style
A professor that actually teaches, and teaches well, too.
No Comments
one of the few really good teachers here
The prof is pretty good, but the material is quite tough.
Fun guy to have for Calc II for P. Sci Majors
Dr. Thomas Colonna is a great professor. I enjoyed his classes and presentations enormousely. I would take them again if I had the choice. One of the best at JHU

Dr. Colonna is a superb professor. His class is a tremendous opportunity for students to learn from an expert in the field, who is extremely talented in teaching the material in a clear and engaging way. In addition, he clearly cares about his class and students, and wants them to succeed. Dr. Colonna is excellent!

No lectures, instead he will do a few chats a semester (optional). He definitely has a sense of humor and he will demonstrate it in his case studies. Case studies do take time as you have to evaluate & assess something ridiculous.  Case studies are way futuristicsci-fi inspired, so even the FDA Center Directors can't help you (yes, I called them)

Took Syntax I with Prof. Legendre. Very knowledgeable and passionate in linguistics. She cares about her students: very accessible and patient during class/office hours and would spend time in class going over the assignments. Syntax is HARD and get ready to spend tons of time --- don't take it unless you are really interested.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Get ready to read

comment: She was passionate but doesn't know how to teach introductory level material: no one understood the rules and people fell quickly behind. Homeworks are above our comprehension level for an introductory course, and take up to 10 hours a week. Do not take this course if you want an easy class or something that will not stress you out.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: She is one of the most passionate teachers that I ever had. Her classes are not easy, but if you try, you will do well. I love her!!

Prof Legendre has such a passion for her work and linguistics and she definitely brought that passion to class. The content in the class is fairly complex and most people seemed to LOVE class or HATE it, there wasn't much in between. I would definitely recommend to anyone  interested in how languages work but definitely NOT an "easy N credit".

Hands down, one of the best professors I have had and will have! Extremely helpful, might appear strict at first but is very easy going and warm. Takes interest in student's performance and knows her subject in and out. Highly recommend taking WOL with her!
Great Professor. When Needed help she was readily available. TA's are helpful. Great class very interesting. Just dont allow yourself to fall behind. Alot of material

A bit disappointed by Phonology this year: Take it if you want low stress and easy pass, reconsider if you want to learn more about linguistics. Few assignments, extremely slow feedback, easy content since we covered many topics in phonology BRIEFLY. Felt like I didn't learn a lot and Prof didn't have high expectations for us anyways.

Taking Cognition with Wilson. Really cool guy, obviously knows a lot about the subject and tries to make it interesting. Unfortunately, a lot of the subject matter is just incredibly lofty and theoretical and nothing is really concrete, even with explanation.
very nice and approachable but class was more based on computers than I thought it would be. Lectures were often dry.

Took Phonology with Wilson. The material was interesting, though I'm not sure what the point was in most of the lectures. Wilson has no clue what his TAs do, and needs to be more aware of how they grade. I was not impressed by how little Wilson knew about the way the class was actually going, as well as about final grades.

Dr. Shelby is an amazing professor. His lectures are clear and thorough. He genuinely cares for his students and takes from his personal time during weekends to support them. The grading is fair, and the discussions are very insightful. I would recommend taking a class with Dr. Shelby any day. He is a wonderful, wonderful person.
Prof Chung is great. Very helpful and accessible. Reading is long but manageable. Her grading is fair.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Inspirational

comment: Super passionate teacher; clearly very knowledgeable about her topic of study. Took her class as a freshman and even though I was obviously  lagging behind my sectionmates, she was super encouraging and never dismissed my views!  Learnt alot.
Very clear lecture--organized, engaging, and relevant.

She doesn't seem to know anything besides Korean immigrants in Japan. In our East Asian Politics class, she just made us read papers and barely taught. For the China part, we had to watch a three day movie because she didn't know anything. Unhelpful and unresponsive to e-mails. Loves her Korean heritage and often is ... extremely biased.

She makes you read the articles then memorize their key points. If you do not memorize the author's names, there was no point in taking any test. The problem wouldn't be so bad if there weren't 200+ pages a week to read. I made a final review sheet which was more than 60 pages long (front/back font: 10). Not an effective class. Do not take it.
She has a nice personality and has some good class discussions, but her lectures aren't very helpful for the difficult exams.

AWFUL!!!! The most horrible professor!!!! Unfair grader! DO NOT TAKE HIS CLASS!!!! He will do everything he can to fail you! He deducts points for incorrect referencing style rather than the knowledge and content you put into your assignments. He was very mean and tried to criticize every discussion post.
